eur Champions: 1985, 2017 <br>\nDivision Sup\u00e9rieure R\u00e9gionale Champions of group A: 2010 <br>\nDivision d'Honneur R\u00e9gionale Runners-up of group A: 2009\n|| Formed out of the merger of [[Racing Club Versaillais]] (founded 1960) and [[Compagnons Sportifs Versaillais]] (founded 1958).\n|-\n| [[FC Fleury 91]] || 1991 || || [[Fleury-M\u00e9rogis]] || ||\n|}\n\n===Women's===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Club\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"350\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100\" | Professional Period\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100\" | Neighbourhood\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"600\" | Honours\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100\" | Note\n|-\n| [[Paris Saint-Germain F\u00e9minines]] || 1971 || || [[16th arrondissement of Paris]] || \nDivision 2 F\u00e9minine (1): 2000\u201301 <br>\nCoupe de France F\u00e9minine (2): 2009\u201310, 2017\u201318 <br>\nChallenge National \u00c9lite U19 (2): 2015\u201316, 2016\u201317 <br>\nGipuzkoa Elite Cup (1): 2018 <br>\n||\n|-\n| [[Paris FC (women)|Paris FC]] || 1971 as ES Juvisy-sur-Orge <br> 1985 as FCF Juvisy Essonne <br> 2017 as Paris FC || 2017- || [[Viry-Ch\u00e2tillon]] || \nDivision 1 F\u00e9minine Champions (6): 1991\u201392, 1993\u201394, 1995\u201396, 1996\u201397, 2002\u201303, 2005\u201306 <br>\nChallenge de France Winners (1): 2005 <br>\nInvitational Menton Tournament Winners (1): 1993 <br>\n||\n|-\n| [[FC Fleury 91 (women)|FC Fleury 91]] || 2003 as FCF Val d'Orge <br> 2017 as FCF 91 C\u0153ur d'Essonne || 2017- || [[Fleury-M\u00e9rogis]] || Division 2 F\u00e9minine Champions: 2017 ||\n|}\n\n==Academies==\n\nThe table below lists all Paris academies not affiliated to clubs.\n\n===Men's===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"50\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"450\" | Note\n|-\n| [[INF Clairefontaine]] || ||\n|}\n\n===Women's===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"150\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"50\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"450\" | Note\n|-\n| [[CNFE Clairefontaine]] || ||\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Football in France]]\n{{Football in France}}\n\n[[Category:Football in Paris| ]]\n[[Category:Football in France|Paris]]\n", "text_old": "'''[[Association football|Football]]''' is the most popular sport, both in terms of participants and spectators, in [[Paris]]. Paris has several of France's significant football clubs, and the city is home to many football clubs. [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.]] is Paris's most successful club.\n\n[[Stade de France]], France's [[national stadium]] is just north of [[Paris]]. It is the home venue of the [[France national football team]] and has traditionally hosted the [[Coupe de France]] [[List of Coupe de France winners|Final]] since 1998.\n\n4 clubs based in Paris [[Racing Club de France football Colombes 92|RC Paris]], [[Club Fran\u00e7ais]], [[Red Star F.C.]] and [[CA Paris-Charenton]] participated in [[1932\u201333 French Division 1]] as founding members.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesf/franchamp.html#orig |title=Origins of the French League |publisher=RSSF.com |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Derbies==\nThe last derby proper in French top-flight football, [[Football in Paris#Paris derbies|Paris derby]] took place during the [[Ligue 1]] [[1989\u201390 French Division 1|1989-90 season]] between [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] and [[Racing Club de France football Colombes 92|Racing Paris]]. for 5 seasons in [[Ligue 1|First division]]. In total they met regularly for 5 seasons ([[1984\u201385 French Division 1|1984\u201385 season]] and [[1986\u201387 French Division 1|1986\u201387]] to [[1989\u201390 French Division 1|1989\u201390 season]] continuously).\n\nThe only regularly occurring city derbies and which uphold their rivalries in recent years are the Parisian derbies between [[Red Star F.C.|Red Star]], [[US Cr\u00e9teil-Lusitanos|US Cr\u00e9teil]] and [[Paris FC]]<ref>http://www.whatsthefoot.com/le-red-star-remporte-le-derby-capital/</ref> in the second and third tiers.\n\n== Clubs ==\n\nThe table below lists all Paris clubs.\n\n===Men's===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100\" | Club\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"40\" | Founded\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100\" | Professional Period\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"100\" | Neighbourhood\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"600\" | Honours\n! scope=\"col\" width=\"400\" | Note\n|-\n| [[Club Fran\u00e7ais]] || 1890 || 1932\u20131934 || || USFSA Champions Champions: 1896 <br> Coupe de France Final: 1931 || Defunct in 1935\n|-\n| [[US Suisse Paris]] || 1894 || 1934\u20131935 || [[Porte Dauphine]] || USFSA Champions Runner up: 1903\u201304 <br> Coupe Dewar winner: 1903 || [[Swiss migration to France|Swiss expatiate]] club, founding member of the Ligue \u00cele-de-France and the French Football Federation\n|-\n| [[Standard Athletic Club]] || 1890 || 1890-1937 || [[Meudon]] || USFSA Champions: 1894, 1895, 1897, 1898, 1901 || [[British migration to France|British expatriate]] social club; founding participant [[Coupe de France]] 1917\n|-\n| [[Racing Club de France football Colombes 92|Racing Paris]] || 1896 || 1932\u20131967, 1983\u20131990 || [[Colombes]] || Ligue 1 Champions (1) 1936 <br> Ligue 1 Runners-up (2): 1961, 1962 <br> Ligue 2 Champions (1): 1986 <br> Championnat de France amateur Winners (1): 2004 (Group D) <br> Championnat de France amateur 2 Winners (1): 2007 (Group F) <br> Division d'Honneur (Paris \u00cele-de-France) Champions (1): 1973 <br> Coupe de France Champions (5): 1936, 1939, 1940, 1945, 1949 <br> Coupe de France Runners-up (3): 1930, 1950, 1990 <br> USFSA Championnat\nChampions (1): 1907 <br> USFSA Paris Championnat Champions (6): 1902, 1903, 1907, 1908, 1911, 1919 <br> FFFA Ligue de Paris Champions (2): 1931, 1932 <br> Coupe Dewar Champions (4): 1905, 1906, 1